        <prj:TechnicalJustification>
            <prj:justificationText>For the continuum observations, we employ the largest bandwidths available in the ALMA correlator setting in the FDM mode. We cannot use the TDM mode in which total bandwidth is the same as our setting but with lower spectral resolution. As mentioned above, there are lot of molecular lines in Orion KL known as the line forest. By using the most extended configuration, we hope to resolve out most of these line emissions from our continuum data. However, there may be unresolved line emissions which are possibly strong compact emissions such as masers, high excitation transitions, and/or very abundant species. To avoid such contamination efficiently, we employ the FDM mode with the velocity resolution of 0.854 km/s to resolve the line profiles.

</prj:justificationText>
            <prj:justificationKey>ED_CORRELATOR</prj:justificationKey>
        </prj:TechnicalJustification>
        <prj:TechnicalJustification>
            <prj:justificationText>We employ a single pointing mode with the most extended configuration with the maximum baseline length of 2 km. Field of view in this mode is sufficient to cover the whole of our target source because it will be a compact continuum emission closely associated with a central YSO. The source size is estimated to be 0.2"*0.1" based on previous VLA 43 GHz observations and CARMA 229 GHz observation (Reid et al. 2007, Goddi et al. 2011, Plambeck et al. 2013). To resolve the structure both in major and minor axes, we definitely need highest resolution at 0.05".
On the other hand, we do not need to recover extended emission component. It is well known that the Orion KL region show number of molecular lines (line forest). These spectral lines could significantly contribute to the continuum emission data unless they are removed in data analysis. In order to avoid such contamination, we try to resolve out as many extended line emissions as possible to employ the longer baselines. Thus, the most extended configuration is the ideal setting for our compact source.
</prj:justificationText>
            <prj:justificationKey>ED_ANGULAR_RESOLUTION</prj:justificationKey>
        </prj:TechnicalJustification>
        <prj:TechnicalJustification>
            <prj:justificationText>Our target source is Orion KL Source I. The source position is taken from our ALMA cycle 0 results (Hirota et al. 2015a).
We estimate the continuum flux density based on our ALMA cycle 0 observations at bands 6 and 7 along with previous data (Plambeck et al. 2013, Figure 3). If we employ the power-law+graybody SED, the total flux density at band 9 is calculated to be 6.23 Jy with the source size of 0.2"*0.1" (Reid et al. 2007, Goddi et al. 2011, Plambeck et al. 2013). The observed peak flux density per beam will be 779 mJy with the beam size of 0.05"*0.05". In the worst case, however, the total flux density could be as small as 1 Jy (i.e. almost the same as that of band 7) because of the turnover in the SED caused by the lower optical depth than we have expected (Figure 3(a)). In this case, observed peak flux density will be 125 mJy. For safety, we set the requested rms noise level of 12.5 mJy (S/N=10) to measure the continuum flux density accurately even in the worst case. Assuming the aggregate bandwidth, the on-source integration time of 2.01 minutes (minimum on-source time) can achieve the higher S/N ratio of 549.3.
In our spectral window, there is a strong H2O maser line at 658 GHz (Hirota et al. 2015b). If we correct for the primary beam attenuation by a factor of 10 (Figure 2), we expect the actual flux density of more than 1000 Jy. It will be detectable within a 2.01 minutes of on-source.
</prj:justificationText>
            <prj:justificationKey>ED_SENSITIVITY</prj:justificationKey>
        </prj:TechnicalJustification>
