        <prj:TechnicalJustification>
            <prj:justificationText>Our target source is Orion KL Source I. The source position is taken from our ALMA cycle 0 results (Hirota et al. 2015a).
We estimate the continuum flux density based on our ALMA cycle 0 observations at bands 6 and 7 along with previous data (Plambeck et al. 2013, Figure 3). If we employ the power-law+graybody SED, the total flux density at band 10 is calculated to be 14.58 Jy with the source size of 0.2"*0.1" (Reid et al. 2007, Goddi et al. 2011, Plambeck et al. 2013). The observed peak flux density per beam will be 1166 mJy with the beam size of 0.04"*0.04". In the worst case, however, the total flux density could be as small as 1 Jy (i.e. almost the same as that of band 7) because of the turnover in the SED caused by the lower optical depth than we have expected (Figure 3(a)). In this case, observed peak flux density will be 80  mJy. For safety, we set the requested rms noise level of 8 mJy (S/N=10) to measure the continuum flux density accurately even in the worst case. Assuming the aggregate bandwidth, the on-source integration time of 2.01 minutes (minimum on-source time) can achieve the S/N ratio of 299.9.
In our spectral window, there are four H2O lines at 899 GHz, 902.4 GHz, 902.6 GHz, and 906 GHz. For these lines, we estimate their flux densities based on our previous cycle 0 observation of the 336 GHz H2O line assuming the excitation temperature of 3000 K (Hirota et al. 2014). The weakest line has a flux density of 0.4 Jy (at 906 GHz). However, we do not consider detectability of these lines because our primary target is the continuum emission. If we detect these lines as strong maser emissions, they are regarded as an extra-success.
