    <prp:abstract>We propose ALMA bands 9 and 10 observations at the highest resolution (0.05") to map continuum emissions associated with a massive YSO Orion KL Source I. &#xd;
In cycle 0, we detected the vibrationally excited H2O line at 336 GHz tracing a rotating gas disk around Source I. We also obtained an evidence of a high temperature gas disk from the continuum SED at bands 6 and 7. The SED agrees with the optically thick emission from the H^- free-free radiation (interaction between neutral hydrogen and electron) with a temperature of 1000-3000 K. However, we could not constrain the source size and brightness temperature due to our insufficient resolution (0.4"). Furthermore, we could not rule out possibilities of an optically thin H^- free-free emission with a turnover or a dust graybody emission with an excess at 690 GHz. Since the difference in the above SED models becomes larger by a factor of 2 at &gt;690 GHz, accurate continuum flux data at ALMA bands 9 and 10 are crucial to distinguish the models. Our spatially resolved continuum maps will help to understand emission mechanisms and properties of the disk around Source I such as the size, temperature, density, and mass. &#xd;
</prp:abstract>
